I generally don't practice the art of "technical analysis," i.e., using price history to predict future stock prices. But I do look at charts, and they are frequently interesting even if not predictive. I don't know what the pattern is called (maybe a pennant?) but the TSLA price is generally in a steep uptrend. But it has approached $450 a couple of times and failed to punch through. That, I believe is called a "resistance level."

Despite record production, super-ambitious year end targets, an anticipated Biden EV boom and the halo of battery day, Tesla is not really joining in the Nasdaq rebound. Given that their biggest independent shareholder Baillie Gifford has cashed in a few days before the September sell-off, I do not feel like Tesla can sustain this level until the end of the year. It's now mainly "suckers" holding the bag, not the kind of investors who can stomach a 1065 price earnings ratio if there is a "limit down" event. This is at this stage purely a gut feeling, not anything I have meticulously pieced together from tail hedge pricing or order book dynamics or anything of that sort. But it could be rewarding both financially and Brier-wise to dig deeper. Any strong views for / against?

Stock split means shares are now in the mid-$400 range instead of over $1000. Moreover, it hit a low of $408 today after dropping over 15% at one point, meaning it was very close to dropping below the $400 mark. While daily fluctuations do not mean much in the longterm, the fact that one can be so extreme is cause for concern. More importantly, however, the tech boom that reinvigorated the market months ago is beginning to cool and Tesla's current P/E ratio is over 1100, which is insane. This essentially means that the yearly earnings available to shareholders are more than 1000 times lower than the price of each stock. Most savvy investors look for stocks with P/E ratios closer to 10-15 and avoid those over 25. Name recognition and its past performance could keep the price up for a while, but its likely to come crashing down sooner or later. In reality, Tesla hasn't turned a profit in any of the last 4 fiscal years, so its current investors are really banking on the future. If the market crashes, however, I think Tesla falls hard and fast.

Due to momentum and market sentiment, Tesla Inc. will continue to appear a success story. Financials are weak and fixed capital investment is costly, but will not become an issue. Tesla could easily raise new equity through different channels, when hostile takeovers may become interesting in the industry. Similar to Apple earlier, Tesla understands to engage the media for its purposes and has hardly any cost for marketing and nevertheless much attention in the news. Its premium only-strategy seems to work out: product pricing is still in the upper range on average, still the product appears desirable to customers. Electrification, digitalisation and expansion of mobile communications into every aspect of everyday life promises lots of opportunities for secondary businesses. It is, due to past squeezes in Tesla stock, at present more of a risk NOT to be invested in Tesla for large and institutional investors, which lays a floor at, say, 300USD. Possible news concerning a proprietary crypto currency for internal accounting would make sense to me in the near term, which could further justify valuation (which is not justified at the moment but a big bet on 2025 or later). Possible regulatory issues and actions with governments (especially in Europe) is the largest downside risk, but so far Tesla has been treated very benevolent. Moreover, Teslas success seems to be of special interest and under protection of the US government.
